To calculate the speed during jogging based on the given IMU acceleration data, we can use the magnitude of the acceleration along the x-axis as an estimate for the forward velocity component since it's likely that most of the movement occurs in the horizontal plane.

The maximum value of the filtered acceleration along axis X was found at index 104 which corresponds to time = 2 seconds.
 
 Acceleration_x_max = 1 m/s^2 * 2g =  2 meters per second squared 

However, considering only the highest recorded acceleration might not be sufficient to accurately determine the jogger’s actual walking speed because there may have been brief periods where they accelerated more rapidly than others. To get a better understanding of their overall pace, let's look at other statistics like RMS values:

RMS acceleration_x = 0 m/s² * sqrt(1.35) ≈ 1 meter per second square root of 1 point three five.

